Calcined petroleum coke (1–2cm, source: Slovakia), was purchased from Resorbent S.R.O (Ostrava, Czech Republic). Sulfuric acid (96%, w/w), nitric acid (68, w/w) and sodium hydroxide (>99%, p.a.) were obtained from Penta (Prague, Czech Republic). Dialysis membranes (Visking, MWCO 14kDa) were purchased from P-LAB (Prague, Czech Republic). Tris(hydroxymethyl)aminomethane, sodium chloride, potassium chloride and hydrochloric acid (37%, w/w) were procured from Sigma–Aldrich (Singapore). Magnesium chloride hexahydrate was obtained from Quality Reagent Chemical (Auckland, New Zealand). Deionized water (16.8MΩcm) was utilized for GQD synthesis and purification. Tris–HCl buffer (20mM, pH 7.4) was prepared by dissolving NaCl (100mM), KCl (5mM) and MgCl2 (5mM) in milli-Q water (18.2MΩ cm), and was utilized for all spectroscopic detection experiments. DNA oligonucleotides were procured from Sigma–Aldrich (Singapore). The nucleic acid sequences are enumerated below:


FAM-Lprobe:



5′ [6FAM] ACC AGG CGG CCG CAC ACG TCC TCC AT 3′;



Complementary DNA target, cDNA:



5′ ATG GAG GAC GTG TGC GGC CGC CTG GT 3′;

XPS was carried out to examine the surface chemical composition and bonding configurations within the GQD materials (Fig. 3
                        ) [72,73]. XPS results showed that the GQDs contained mainly C and O elements, with a C/O ratio of 1.63. In addition to π–π stacking interactions and hydrophobic interactions, the extensive oxygen functionalities present on GQDs also promotes the adsorption of single-stranded DNA onto the GQDs, via hydrogen-bonding interactions with the DNA nucleobases [74]. High resolution C 1s scans uncovered the presence of CC, CC, CO, CO, and OCO peaks, suggesting the presence of hydrophobic regions as well as hydrophilic hydroxyl, carbonyl and carboxylic acid functionalities in the GQDs. The large abundance of hydrophilic moieties in the GQDs greatly enhances the solubility of GQDs in aqueous solutions and supports their applications in aqueous systems (Table 1
                        ).
